[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-00789, St. Moritz, Eisstadion.jpg|thumb|right|The stadium in 1928]]
'''St. Moritz Olympic Ice Rink''' ({{lang-de|Eisstadion Badrutts Park}}) is an outdoor [[stadium]] in [[St. Moritz]], [[Switzerland]].  It was the venue for the [[ice hockey]], [[speedskating]] and [[figure skating]] events, as well as the location of the opening and closing ceremonies at the [[1928 Winter Olympics]] and [[1948 Winter Olympics]].<ref>[http://www.aircanada.com/en/onair/february2010/eng-can-2/top5.html "Best Hosts of Olympic Winter Games Past"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606111804/http://www.aircanada.com/en/onair/february2010/eng-can-2/top5.html |date=2011-06-06 }}, ''onAir'' magazine, Air Canada, February 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1928/1928w2.pdf 1928 Winter Olympics official report.] Part 2. pp. 1-7, 15. {{fr icon}}</ref><ref>[http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1948/ORW1948.pdf 1948 Winter Olympics official report.] pp. 6, 21, 23. {{fr icon}} & {{de icon}}</ref>

Artist and designer [[Rolf Sachs]] now owns the stadium's former land, and the building containing the changing facilities for athletes and officials and observation facility serves as his personal home.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/12/15/sport/st-moritz-switzerland-olympic-stadium-skiing-alpine-edge/index.html|title=St. Moritz: Meet the man who lives in an Olympic stadium|last=MacFarlane|first=Christina|date=15 December 2017|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>

